. <br>(-74hp)<br><br>In addition to maximum hit points, higher CON also plays a role in reducing damage received in combat.<br><br><br>* Stat QUI Effects *<br><br>Infiltrators will have 60 average QUI, neither decreasing style damage nor increasing rate of attacks.<br><br>Shadowblades will have 60 average QUI, neither decreasing style damage nor increasing rate of attacks.<br><br>Nightsades will have 77.5 average QUI, decreasing style damage, but slightly increasing rate of attacks. (Benefit is that unstyled, Nightshades will attack slightly faster, but styled damage suffers). The additional quickness adds approximately 0.7% chance of evasion at level 50, for a base of 35.7% evade chance.<br><br><br><br>&gt;&gt;&gt; Interruption Analysis Summary &lt;&lt;&lt;<br><br>Unique ability alone, Infiltrators come out on top. Shadowblades bonus hit points almost equals the damage rate of the Nightshade.<br><br>Statwise, Infiltrator stats on average can supply better base bonus to damage, but slight loss in hit points compared to the Shadowblade, almost a fair comparison in stats alone. Nightshades are negatively affected in 2 of 3 areas, having –17.5 STR/CON on average, and it is debateable how beneficial +QUI really is (please don’t use this to ask for a self-buff, ick!)<br><br><br>* Damage Types: *<br><br>Infiltrators can specialize in Thrust or Slash almost equally well (more leaning towards Thrust), through race selection. Thrust for Infiltrators has 5 targets to choose from that have a +15% penalty, and Slash has 2 targets to choose from that have a +15% penalty.<br><br>Shadowblades can specialize in only Slash weapons, but have 2 banks of styles from which to choose from and also adds to 2-handed damage should they opt to use it, with Norse best supporting the bonus damage. Slash for Shadowblades has 3 targets to choose from that have a +15% penalty. IF Shadowblades had Crush, they would have 10 targets to choose form that have a +10% penalty to Crush, and no armor type has bonuses against crush whatsoever. IF Shadowblades had Pierce, they would have 3 targets to choose from that have a +15% penalty (Mercs, Clerics, Minstrels).<br><br>Nightshades can specialize in Thrust or Slash, but will always be at a –20/30 STR disadvantage when choosing Slash, which almost forces all Nightshades to only pick Thrust. Thrust for Nightshades has 8 targets to choose from that have a +15% penalty, and Slash has 3 targets to choose from that have a +15% penalty.<br><br>Damage Type / Style Bank / Non-Style Perks<br>Infiltrator:<br>Slash / Slash / 3 targets<br>Thrust / Thrust / 5 targets<br>Nightshade:<br>Blades / Slash / 3 targets<br>Pierce / Thrust / 8 targets<br>Shadowblade:<br>Sword / Slash / 3 targets / 2-h option<br>Axes / Slash / 3 targets / 2-h option<br>Iff:<br>Hammer/ Crush / 10 targets / 2-h option<br><br>With adding the Shadowblade Iff, just glance at the raw visual quantity of options that gives Shadowblades. 2 damage types with 3 style banks each that have 2-h options, while other realms have 2 damage types and 2 style banks.<br><br>&gt;&gt;&gt; Interruption Analysis Summary &lt;&lt;&lt;<br><br>Infiltrators have 2 damage types which each lead to a bank of styles designated for it.<br><br>Nightshades also have 2 damage types which each lead to a bank of styles designated for it, but almost all Nightshades are pierce because 33.3% of blade styles are based off shields and the stat penalty. Nightshades do get the most targets to choose from weak to thrust by +3 targets, but inherent Nightshade weakness versus the class types that wear Chain area reason Nightshades don’t always go after them.<br><br>Shadowblades have 1 damage type, but 2 banks of styles to choose from for it. Each have the additional perk of increasing 2-h damage. (Key note: it is not a liability, for you are not forced to use it and you can still use it when it is beneficial. It is like saying the Nightshade shout is a liability because the damage is poor and it burns endurance, but you are not forced to use it and can use it when it is beneficial)<br><br>This is why I mentioned in another post that it is a bad idea to give Shadowblades Crush. I know what a 2-h Staff can do unspecialized. It only takes a small amount of specialization in hammer points for a 1-h hammer to beat 2-h Staff damage. I still use a Staff to open up against Plate/Archers in combat just for the damage bonus. It would be even scarier the range of targets Shadowblades would get a bonus against. Slash and pierce has +15% and –15% targets, both having more armors that have bouses against both types more than penalties. However when it comes to crush, there are 10 targets which it has a 10% bonus, and all other armor wearers have NO bonuses against crush weapons whatsoever. Upon respec, every Shadowblade would go Crush.<br><br>Possible Flame Bait: I know I can be called a Shadowblade hater in one post, and biased for Shadowblades in another, and what I present here is likely to get me called a SB hater again by all SBs, but trust me that Crush would overpower SBs. A 10% bonus to 10 targets combined with no penalties whatsoever would increase your average damage by +7.5% in relation to Infs/NS that generally have a –2.5-5% when it comes to armor penalties across the board. Thrust does not add anymore targets for Shadowblades as well.<br><br>I’m being objective here and looking out for your future, you will cause a nerf riot when you are perfing all Plate/Scale Wearers (Armsman, Paladin, Hero, Champion, Warden, Druid) at +10% damage, along with 10% bonus damage to Blademasters, Rangers, Bards, and Scouts, and no penalties. Besides, you still do have 2 banks of styles to choose from (styles aren’t the best, so you can petition to fix those), only 3 classes you face are particulary strong against slash, and 2-h options.<br><br>Instead, I ask Shadowblades focus on ways to improve your primary weapon styles and possibly another minor area, then they should focus on Assassin wide issues. Increased bonus points or adding Hammers is overkill. I’ll go over minor areas that can be addressed later on.<br><br><br><br><br>* Styles *<br><br>Infiltrators will generally have more access to styles with bonus points. Dragonfang is the best evade based style in the game. There are no useful DW styles.<br><br>Shadowblade Left Axe uniquely scales 20% better than DW/CD styles (might get fixed in 1.52, as those styles have been proven to be less than 50% as effective as equivalent weapon styles). They are also the best at applying 2 poisons in combat through how Left Axe functions. Doublefrost, albiet nerfed, still brings on the pain when used, just not having the former glory it once had. Shadowblades to have to spend more points into their offhand for this ability, which does sacrifice from some other area. They can also gain a evade-stun 2 chain, but is more difficult to pull off.<br><br>Nightshades will obtain their evade style Diamondback earlier, but is a short duration stun enough to get a free hit in. There are no useful CD styles, let alone the points to spend for them.<br><br><br>Note: If there is any enhancement in a high end Assassin specialization, you cannot say that fix is always biased towards Infiltrators. Part of the envy generated is the feeling that the Infiltrator can have access to a level 50 Dragonfang in Thrust, or easily obtian 50 Envenom, or benefit from all the level 50 styles. Any choice they make will mean sacrificing possible points into one area for another, so their overall benefit is still in that 15% range that I mentioned earlier. For a similar comparison, it is like saying Humans are overpowered in 3rd Edition D&amp;D rules because they get extra skill points and a bonus feat that increases what they have access to, and that any feat added to the game would overpower humans, but the tradeoff is that they do not have any inherent racial bonuses like all the other races do.<br><br><br>* Dual Wield vs Left Axe base scaling *<br><br>I’ve done TONS of testing on this as you probably know, but a patch was released that scaled Left-Axe damage as you increased in level. To what degree, I think MJ is playing hush hush specifically because how much we pick it apart. Knowing Mythic, the acorn doesn’t fall far from the tree, such that it either improves it .25% per level after 20, such that the total bonus goes from 120% to 132.5%, which still has to be determined, which falls short of the 137.5% benefit from Dual Wield.<br><br>I’m not going into the math behind it, but I think 145% is THE fix for the Shadowblades. Instead of just increasing only the left axe component, it increases both by .25% per level. That takes some of the burden away by allowing both primary and offhand weapon to increase damage without having to spend the points into them, for having less points than Infiltrators. That way, Shadowblades don’t need to ask for more points.<br><br><br>* Summary of Fixes *<br><br>Infiltrators are just fine as they are. If there is anything they should be asking for, it might be an analysis of their weapon styles (mostly slash) and dual wield styles. Every other concern is generally an Assassin wide issue.<br><br>Shadowblades, a 12.5% boost to melee damage in the primary I proposed (145% total) along with analysis of your weapon and left axe styles is all that is really needed. That along with the 5% bonus hit points would make you on par with Infiltrators for the benefit they gain with those lost points. Adding more points or adding hammers as a specialization would overpower your class and have tanks and healers screaming bloody nerf. After receiving the melee damage boost, Shadowblades’ primary concerns should be Assassin wise issues.<br><br>Nightshades are proven weaker in melee, hit points, damage taken, style damage/access, or amazing styles to choose from, but do have the most amount of targets that have a thrust penalty. CD styles are terrible of course, but 33.3% of slash is based off Shield, and Pierce has useless long chains that draw out the damage over a longer period of time. Being weaker in Melee damage can be supplement if the Shout base damage was increased to 140, being weaker in defense can be made up for a 175 base nuke, and at most, a new spell. I ask that Nightshades not opt for a self buff to make them artifically fight like Infiltrators and Shadowblades do in melee. It is okay to be weaker toe to toe (some Nightshades out there hate me for saying this), we shouldn’t be clones, as long as there are benefits in different areas for Nightshades to be good at.<br><br><br>Generally my posts analyze a situation and propose fixes. I’m really repeating stuff here that I have always been saying, but I’m trying now to put things in perspective that not all is bad, there’s envy, you can’t have it all, and things aren’t far off from being balanced, and some proposed “fixes” out there are too much. I’m trying to reword things to put it into perspective not to overpower Assassin balance. It is a very delicate thing you have to break down one step at a time and look at how it affects the whole way the class operates. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub175.ezboard.com/uelaa.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Elaa</A> at: 6/30/02 2:19:47 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub175.ezboard.com/uubergnome563.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ubergnome563</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/30/02 2:15:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3657.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> .</span><hr size=1> Yeah that looks pretty good.  Dueled a LA SB (finally... a LA SB) last night and it wasnt even clos